    {
      "id": "4fa0bb6ba5bb90971c77154abfa62749e2893a24",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 124,
        "name": "Prakash Surya",
        "email": "lists@prakashsurya.com",
        "username": "prakash"
      },
      "date": "2013-01-19 01:00:23.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\nNiu, I found somewhat of a reproducer for this by running:\n\n    /usr/sbin/lctl set_param 'osc.*.max_dirty_mb=0'\n\non the IONs while an concurrent IOR is happening. Theads will then pile up on the waitq.\n\nWithout changing 'max_dirty_mb' back to something sane (i.e. 32MB), should those threads ever wake up? I'm trying to cook up a reproducer to test this patch, and this is the closet I've gotten. The only issue is, the threads never wake up (with or without this patch), so I'm not sure if the patch is flawed or my test.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "711ab160a949fd9616b346e0313b9940e45f4df3",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 104,
        "name": "Niu Yawei",
        "email": "yawei.niu@intel.com",
        "username": "niu",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-01-21 04:12:48.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\nHi, Prakash, that should not be a flaw belong to this patch, however, I think we'd address it in this patch. (change max_dirty_mb to zero could cause lots of wakup being lost, see osc_wake_cache_waiters(), it'll return for cli->cl_dirty + CFS_PAGE_SIZE > cli->cl_dirty_max).",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
